<div id="pf2bbc" class="pf w4d h238" data-page-no="2bbc"><div class="pc pc2bbc w4d h238"><div class="t m127 x11 h27 y2c96 ff4 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">2. </div><div class="t ma20 x73 h27 y2c96 ff4 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Which event was, according to </div><div class="t m268 x3 h27 y2af5 ff4 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Peter&apos;s words, a major theme of the </div><div class="t m1631 x3 h27 y2a9e ff4 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">prophets of old? Acts 3:19-21. </div><div class="t m5b4 x27 he y238c ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NOTE.,—&quot;The dominant theme of the NT </div><div class="t me9e x3 he y234f ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">writers is the return of Christ. . . . The </div><div class="t me29 x3 he y15b5 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">disciples had witnessed Christ&apos;s ascension </div><div class="t m850 x3 he y385 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(ch. 1:9, 10), and they realized He must </div><div class="t mcf6 x3 he yf4 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">remain in heaven until His second advent. </div><div class="t m7ba x3 he y1b52 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Jesus had told His disciples that it was </div><div class="t m68c x3 he y2b0 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">necessary for Him to leave them (John 14: </div><div class="t m582 x3 he y15b6 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">1-6), but even they did not understand until </div><div class="t m6e9 x3 he y313 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">they saw Him ascend, and learned that </div><div class="t mdd0 x3 he y14b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">they must look for His return.&quot;—The </div><div class="t m366 x2f h21 y14b ff6 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Sev-</div><div class="t m2bb x3 h21 y946 ff6 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">enth-day Adventist Bible Commentary, </div><div class="t m5c9 x1e he y946 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">on </div><div class="t m42f x3 he ya2b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Acts 3:20, 21. </div><div class="t mf3e x4a h1 y55a ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Forcefully Set Forth by the </div><div class="t m6c4 x55 h1 y317 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Apostle Paul </div><div class="t m2b6 x11 h27 y6c0 ff4 fs7 f